===Etymology 1===
Via {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|rai|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|radius||staff, stake, spoke|lang=la}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[beam]] of light or [[radiation]].
#: ''I saw a '''ray''' of light through the clouds.''
# {{context|zoology|lang=en}} A [[rib]]-like [[reinforcement]] of [[bone]] or [[cartilage]] in a fish's [[fin]].
# {{context|zoology|lang=en}} One of the [[spheromere]]s of a [[radiate]], especially one of the arms of a [[starfish]] or an [[ophiuran]].
# {{context|botany|lang=en}} A radiating part of a flower or plant; the [[marginal]] [[floret]]s of a compound flower, such as an [[aster]] or a [[sunflower]]; one of the [[pedicel]]s of an [[umbel]] or other circular flower cluster; [[radius]].
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} Sight; perception; vision; from an old theory of vision, that sight was something which proceeded from the eye to the object seen.
#* Alexander Pope
#*: All eyes direct their '''rays''' / On him, and crowds turn coxcombs as they gaze.
# {{context|mathematics|lang=en}} A line extending indefinitely in one direction from a point.
# {{context|colloquial|lang=en}} A tiny amount.
#: ''Unfortunately he didn't have a '''ray''' of hope''.

